  'name-compatibility': {
    whatIs: "A Name Love Compatibility calculator tests romantic chemistry between two names using three fun methods: the classic FLAMES game (Friends, Lovers, Affection, Marriage, Enemies, Soulmates), vowel harmony analysis, and name numerology. FLAMES has been played by schoolchildren worldwide for generations — you write two names, cross out common letters, count the remainder, and cycle through F-L-A-M-E-S to reveal the relationship type. Our calculator automates this nostalgic game and adds two additional algorithms for a more complete (but equally unscientific) compatibility analysis.",
    howItWorks: "Enter two names. The FLAMES algorithm: (1) removes all common letters from both names, (2) counts remaining letters, (3) cycles through F→L→A→M→E→S counting that many positions, removing the letter landed on, and continuing until one letter remains. Vowel Harmony scores how many matching vowel sounds the names share. Name Numerology converts each name to a number, compares the difference, and derives a compatibility sub-score. The three methods are weighted into one overall percentage.",
    formula: "FLAMES Algorithm:\n1. Remove common letters: 'Alice' + 'Bob' → remove shared letters → count remaining\n2. Cycle: count remaining through FLAMES, removing each hit\n3. Last letter = result: Friends/Lovers/Affection/Marriage/Enemies/Soulmates\n\nVowel Harmony: count shared vowels ÷ max vowels × 10 = star rating\n\nName Numerology: |sum(name1 letters) − sum(name2 letters)| mod 100 → compatibility\n\nOverall Score = (FLAMES score × 0.5) + (Vowel score × 0.3) + (Numerology score × 0.2)\nClamped to 10-99% range",
    useCases: ["Nostalgic fun: remember playing FLAMES in middle school?", "Testing crush compatibility with a name-based love test", "Party icebreaker: have everyone pair up and check name compatibility", "Wedding shower game: test the bride and groom's names", "Classroom fun: a lighthearted activity for students"],
    tips: ["FLAMES works best with first names only — adding middle or last names changes the letter count and therefore the result", "The original FLAMES game uses paper and pencil — there's something satisfyingly tactile about crossing out letters. Our digital version captures the algorithm but the manual version has more charm", "For a fun twist: try different versions of your names (full name vs. nickname, with and without middle name) and see how the result changes", "Name compatibility is 100% unscientific and 100% entertaining. A 'Soulmates' FLAMES result doesn't mean you should propose, and an 'Enemies' result doesn't mean you should break up"],
    faq: [
      { q: "What does FLAMES stand for?", a: "F = Friends, L = Lovers, A = Affection, M = Marriage, E = Enemies, S = Soulmates. The game originated as a schoolyard pastime (uncertain exact origin, but widely played globally since at least the 1970s). Different cultures have variations with different words and meanings." },
      { q: "Can I get different results with different name spellings?", a: "Yes — 'Katherine' and 'Catherine' will give different results because they contain different letters. Try nicknames, middle names, or alternate spellings for fun. Some people strategically choose which name version to use!" },
    ],
  },

  'love-calculator': {
    whatIs: "A Love Calculator is the classic online entertainment tool — enter two names and get a 'love percentage' score with a playful analysis. This timeless internet trope has existed since the early days of the web (circa 1999), generating millions of giggles, awkward moments between friends, and brave crush confessions over two decades. Our modern version uses a deterministic hashing algorithm seeded by the input names — meaning the SAME two names always produce the SAME result (so you and your crush will see the same number). It's completely unscientific, delightfully nostalgic, and still the fastest way to start a conversation about that special someone.",
    howItWorks: "Enter two names. The calculator: (1) normalizes the names (lowercase, remove non-letters), (2) computes a deterministic hash from the character codes of both names, (3) maps this hash through a prime-number transformation to produce a score between 11% and 99% — never 100% (perfection is overrated) and never 0% (everyone deserves a chance), (4) selects a playful verdict message. The same names will always give the same score, so you can screenshot and share — your crush will see the same result if they try it.",
    formula: "seed = Σ charCodes(name1) × Σ charCodes(name2)\nscore = ((seed × 7919 + 104729) % 89) + 11\n\nProperties:\n• Deterministic: same names = same score always\n• Range: 11% to 99% (11+0 through 11+88)\n• Distribution: uniform across the 11-99 range\n• Impossible values: 0-10% and 100%\n• 7919 and 104729 are prime numbers (for proper hashing)\n\nVerdict messages:\n95%+ → Legendary love\n85-94% → Strong chemistry\n70-84% → Sweet connection\n50-69% → Worth exploring\n30-49% → Maybe just friends\n<30% → The numbers aren't feeling it",
    useCases: ["Testing your name with your crush's name (the classic use case)", "Fun at parties: have everyone test compatibility with everyone else", "Social media: share your love score screenshot and tag your partner/friend", "Anniversary fun: couples checking their 'official' love percentage", "Icebreaker: 'Hey, our love calculator says we're 87% compatible'"],
    tips: ["Try different name variations: first name only, full name, nickname. Different combinations give different results — find your highest score!", "The algorithm is deterministic, so if you and your crush both enter the same names, you'll see the same score. This makes it feel more 'real' than a purely random generator", "Screen-shot your result and share it — the playful verdict messages are designed to be screenshot-friendly social content", "Enter a celebrity's name with yours for a fun parasocial love test. Yes, we've all done it. No, it doesn't count as meeting them"],
    faq: [
      { q: "Is the love calculator real?", a: "It's real in the sense that it really exists and really generates a number. It's not real in the sense of having any scientific validity whatsoever. The algorithm is designed for consistency (same input = same output) and entertainment value — not for predicting actual romantic compatibility." },
      { q: "Why can't I get 100%?", a: "Because even the most legendary love has room to grow! The maximum is deliberately capped at 99% — that last 1% is what you build together through shared experiences. And mathematically, our algorithm's range is 11-99%." },
    ],
  },

